{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "df6af38e-8c33-4fbd-ba0c-ef33ffe47211", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e07d5644eed29938234c82bb21e00a9a800722f810008e8e28a6ef2dd9bad286"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "MooMc32", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-21", "title": null, "content": "Hate to be cliche and be another one who says \"the book is better than the movie!!\" But that truly is the case here.\n\nThe first half of the movie felt like a weird low budget film that was just trying to set up a scene of Sydney Sweeney topless. It was weird vibes and just really felt rushed until her intimate scene.\n\nAfter that, it actual felt like the real thriller story it should have been.\n\nWith that said, maybe I'm just not a Sydney Sweeney fan... I found her acting to be so dry and dull. Amanda on the other hand saved the entire film and was great.\n\nThe film overall was bleh. If I hadn't read the book, I would think it was fine. But remembering how into the book I was, it fell short for me. I wouldn't rewatch it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "561b99a9-fcf1-4b2c-9622-d23e8914288a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4491c38969d224646b1c421884fbd4456c7a8b1312c0fe710a9d659e69aa298f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Elmoonthego", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is ridiculously fun, so contrived but ever so entertaining. This in part is helped by the go for broke acting of the leads, especially Seyfried. From the get go it is obvious who the real villain of the story is, but it is the why that keeps the intrigue intact until the reveal. This is a very much throwaway popcorn movie that delivers the goods. In the olden days it would be just the actresses giving the T & A, but now the guys get to show a bit of flesh too ... lol. This isn't any prestige movie, but it provides a fun and entertaining time at the movies."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c7014d88-86b9-4478-a835-afba088c96ac", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a24a6347b9bbe180e142eea2c9e5b77a876f090839ea2658d3a6622c11bc6983"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "PerryAtTheMovies", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "6.9/10 (7) (Definitely Recommend)\n\nI went into this movie with very little expectations, or even understanding of what I was getting myself into. Some people may know what to expect, and others may not. I aim to write this review trying to keep the mystery. After having seen only the same trailer a bunch of times, I already had a bunch of preconceived notions of what was going to happen, but damn, they were off.\n\nAmanda Seyfried's character was nowhere near where I believed her to be according to the trailer. Amanda is fantastic in the role, and became likeable for me by the end. Sydney Sweeney was once again a little rough/rigid around the edges. However, her acting style fit this character. I was surprised by her characters progression throughout the story. From the trailer alone, I didn't know almost anything about Brandon Sklenar's character, but by the end you knew exactly who he was and why things aren't always as they appear.\n\nThe story was interesting for me. I only found out after the movie that this is a book adaptation, so people like her and her book club knew somewhat of what to expect. Me personally, again, because I didn't know what to expect, was almost bored out of my mind for the first two acts of the film. I honestly thought, and told my sister and her friends, that I believed that this was just another film for Sydney Sweeney to show off her body. While that may have very well been part of the case, by the third act it wasn't the only case. Everything about the movie got more exciting and interesting. I actually became more invested when the onion was being peeled back.\n\nOverall, I would probably see this movie again. The story is better than just some housemaid being put through the wringer. The actin isn't out of this world, but it gets the job done with its tension and release. I think the less you know the better going in, as it certainly helped me enjoy myself. My sister did say the movie differed in some ways compared to the book so even her and her friends were a little taken aback by some of the changes. So if you're looking for a film to watch during the Christmas break, then this is one to certainly check out.\n\nThat's it for now. Thanks for taking time to read my review. Happy watching and enjoy the show!\n\nPS Warning: if you, or someone you know, has been affected or suffered abuse in the past, this film may not be suitable for you. There are some scenes viewers may find graphic when it comes to abuse."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "379882c3-c239-4ee3-8cb6-0b205770a5dd", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e4d021acd533a419475faab521bf9c7351a6bed1ed86673dbfe04e4994beaa0c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "nERDbOX_Dave", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid arrives with a curious mix of expectations and skepticism. Sydney Sweeney's recent box office outings haven't exactly set the world on fire, and opening opposite the latest Avatar installment doesn't do the film any favors commercially. Going in, expectations are understandably tempered. But surprisingly, The Housemaid doesn't take long to find its footing and when it does, it leans hard into its psychological thrills.\n\nThe real engine of the film is Amanda Seyfried, who delivers a chillingly unhinged performance as Nina Winchester, a wealthy housewife whose polished exterior begins to fracture almost immediately. Seyfried plays Nina with a simmering instability... her smiles linger too long, her outbursts hit without warning, and her behavior steadily escalates from eccentric to outright disturbing. It's one of those performances where you're constantly bracing for the next emotional whiplash.\n\nSydney Sweeney stars as Millie Calloway, a young woman with a troubled past who takes a live-in housekeeping job out of sheer necessity. Millie is observant, cautious, and quietly unsettled by Nina's erratic behavior, but her fragile position in life makes walking away impossible. Sweeney's performance is restrained, sometimes almost too much so, but that muted quality works early on as Millie tries to survive rather than confront what's happening around her.\n\nAs expected, Andrew Winchester (Brandon Sklenar) enters the equation, and the film follows a familiar erotic-thriller path: lingering looks, late-night drinks, and one bad decision that sends Nina spiraling. At this point, The Housemaid feels like it's heading toward a predictable third-act meltdown.\n\nThat's where the film earns its credit.\n\nInstead of saving its biggest twist for the finale, The Housemaid flips the script near the end of the second act, shifting the narrative focus squarely onto Millie. From that moment on, the film becomes something darker and far more interesting. The power dynamics change, motivations are recontextualized, and Millie's character steps fully into the spotlight.\n\nWhile this isn't Sydney Sweeney's strongest individual performance, her chemistry with Brandon Sklenar is what ultimately elevates the film. Together, they give the latter half of The Housemaid a sharper edge, grounding the psychological turns in something more emotionally believable. Their scenes add tension without relying solely on shock value, allowing the story's darker implications to breathe.\n\nDirector Paul Feig, stepping away from comedy, handles the genre shift with confidence. The film is sleek, intimate, and deliberately uncomfortable, leaning into paranoia and emotional manipulation rather than outright violence. It may not reinvent the erotic thriller, but it understands the genre well enough to play with audience expectations.\n\nThe Housemaid isn't flawless, and it won't silence every criticism aimed at Sweeney's recent career trajectory. But thanks to Amanda Seyfried's standout performance and a well-timed narrative twist, it's far more compelling than it initially appears."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a0de232f-c3f2-4086-8c49-4965a7b0abdf", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "dee078196dff64c2be21a464b4645490ef8ab8d14b3e3df5969787b3251d1e52"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "jimludwig", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-28", "title": null, "content": "I realize things have to build but it was pretty lackluster until the twist. I did listen to the audiobook and figured out a main component of the twist very early on so that detracts from my enjoyment. I never find nudity necessary in a movie and it is always thrown in for purely prurient reasons and cheapens a movie. If you want a sex movie go watch one it is not needed in regular movies to show that sex occurred."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1964bb8f-3ac2-44b4-b1dc-1691e8d77d0b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "390fcb7c826d39c4997b4f4367717e38e967adfdf76f2a4d7f18c6cc09d11e95"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "viggoped-26934", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-17", "title": null, "content": "As a huge fan of the book, the movie didn't disappoint me at all! The character portrayals were spot on. Especially Seyfrieds performance as Nina, hand her that Oscar already!!!\n\nI still prefer the book. But the movie actually lived up to my expectations & maybe even more!\n\nI think I actually prefer the ending of the movie over the ending of the book!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "72e56410-77b4-472d-8a01-ce4834081ed5", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a760ba05af2af40583ff0433b1524159d2366464c651988b7d174086acdcaacd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Asupiking", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-02", "title": null, "content": "The film starts in a familiar territory, but gradually proves to be more engaging than expected. At first, I assumed It would be the typical film about a familiar psychological drama, but it goes much further than that. Although the first half of the movie does not bring many new elements, it manages to keep you engaged and makes you pay attention to certain details. From that point on, there are some very effective plot twists.\n\nI enjoyed it quite a lot. The actors did a solid job, especially Amanda Seyfried, who felt very realistic when her emotions intensified, while Sydney and Brandon also performed well."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "903fade6-1795-4ba1-b778-f93c320b17b6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f82e30d6f14e7e21418618eb1651ced5bb9c0d53c44d5f3faec0fb930a194946"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "kunalmshah", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-27", "title": null, "content": "I don't understand why this is being underplayed. This movie was very very good. Acting, cinematography, direction, production...it was all superb. Amanda seyfried acted ridiculously well to me. Sidney Sweeney had an amazing role. The pace and development of the characters was great. Felt gripped the whole time. Bravo!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5859d9bb-e68e-4262-8f6d-307f1617b61e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.250150", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3cddfdf62e1a1298526330c0454995eadd986e5112bcc9d8f121906a91c53f05"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "filmephile", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "The film follows a young woman who becomes a housemaid for a wealthy family. Soon the housemaid finds out that there's more than meets the eye.\n\nWhat carries this film are the three central performances from Sweeney, Seyfried, and Sklenar. Seyfried is a particular standout, aptly balancing instability here in the first part of the film, and a kind of charm and gentleness later. It's also nice that the two female leads aren't just ditzy and have some interiority.\n\nAs long as you don't take it too seriously, you'll have a good time. The suspense, tension, and dread ratchet up slowly until it reaches an explosive, satisfying ending. The twists are shocking and unexpected. The film is unpredictable and pleasingly chaotic at times. (Disclaimer: I didn't read the source material.) The action scenes are cool and at times graphic, and the romance is hot.\n\nThis is not only a fun little thriller, but it also has some substance to it. It can be cathartic and poignant at points. It's not often that mainstream films portray domestic violence in the upper echelons of society, and this film does that while simultaneously offering an entertaining time. I myself was in an abusive relationship not too long ago, with a good-looking, successful, and wealthy person similar to the abuser depicted in this film, that lasted for several years. Like the family in this film, we lived in the suburbs where no one suspected a thing, but of course underneath that manicured exterior he was abusing me. It was relatable and refreshing to see my experience represented on screen.\n\nMind you, this film is by no means perfect. It feels campy and cheesy for much of the runtime due to the extremity of some actions taken by characters. And the couple sex scenes feel gratuitous. But at the same time, that can all be forgiven as the extremeness and high tension only adds to the fun in this little popcorn flick.\n\nAnd for those who've been in abusive relationships, particularly with wealthy partners, this film offers the added benefit of being therapeutic. You should know that you're not alone, that there is help out there, and you can always leave the abuse behind.\n\nEnjoy this throwback to the thrillers of the 90s. It's fun."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "83fb046b-8ed7-4a4e-8e31-15ef44d628e9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1d2bdd69fa9b4005f2c710bfd7993bbef5aa2ab1686e3eb735e0ed9274627062"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "marypiatt61489", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "I listened to the audiobook summer of 2023 and was introduced to Freida McFadden. This movie follows the book extremely well and even though I couldn't remember every detail from the book, I recalled the main events. It's a decent movie and I appreciate its similarity to the book (probably because McFadden was an executive producer on this). Worth the watch!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9c9bfd5b-cb9d-4585-86a8-b435ed9d3af6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "61c3df500ce5bcd2a031f1b61a49413c5f15c6be63e8e4490da064a7b34332ff"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "ferguson-6", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-17", "title": null, "content": "Greetings again from the darkness. Director Paul Feig hit it big with the outrageous comedy BRIDESMAIDS in 2011, and then he got a lot more interesting as a filmmaker by directing screen adaptations of Darcey Bell novels that were so popular with Book Clubs - A SIMPLE FAVOR (2018) and ANOTHER SIMPLE FAVOR (2025). There's no need to mess with a good thing, right? This time he's directing another Book Club favorite, Frieda McFadden's 2022 novel. Adapted for the screen by Rebecca Sonnenshine, the movie subjects three gorgeous actors to some off-the-chart twisted and devious turns.\n\nSydney Sweeney stars as Millie, a young parolee who we see arrive at a stunning mansion (fabricated resume in hand) to interview for a live-in housemaid position. Amanda Seyfried is Nina, the lady of the house, and she has prepared a lovely charcuterie board for the interview before taking Millie on a tour of the place ... including the attic room where Millie will be living as she cleans the house, does some light cooking, and sometimes cares for ice-cold young daughter, Cece (Indiana Elle). Millie sleeps in her car until the phone rings with Nina's job offer.\n\nNow, Nina was the dreamboat perfect host and potential employer during the first meeting, but upon Millie's arrival, her temperament has shifted - full bore psychotic mood shifts, replete with throwing dishes, screaming, and false accusations. Of course, Millie must take the abuse and uncertainty or face serving out the rest of her prison sentence - the details come out much later in the film. Still, Millie might just crack if not for the calm, supportive nature of Nina's rich male model-type husband, Andrew (Brandon Sklenar, MIDWAY, 2019).\n\nCommon sense would tell you that the crazy wife vs the desperate housemaid would be enough for a wild story, but oh, how wrong you would be. Things only get crazier from here, and if we've learned one thing sitting through bizarre movies, it's that the best way to execute a preposterous and outlandish story line is to play it (mostly) straight. And that's what we get here. Of course, many of the twists and turns are easy to predict, but that doesn't cut down on the demented fun - even though it jumps the shark a bit.\n\nIt's a fun, wild ride - despite the gaps and the unfortunate lack of substance for supporting characters like Elizabeth Perkins as Andrew's mother, and Michele Morrone as Enzo the groundskeeper. More from either character would have been welcome, although the real star here is Amanda Seyfried who shows incredible range, and never once backs away from the psycho side. I haven't read the book, but for those who have, this film version is more spicy than erotic (save for one hotel scene), and it easily qualifies as a guilty pleasure - especially for those book clubs out there.\n\nOpens in theaters beginning December 19, 2025."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "59fce3df-5100-4f9b-933e-cb6ffe2b6a3b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a8adc23f3ca2a626108eb683f5f0abae562a51a090b5d5d792ce9b3393a6e0f7"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "MariaN-619", "rating": 2, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "So many plot holes in the movie, Sydney Sweeneys voice overs were so monotone that I couldn't care about what was being said, the twist wasn't surprising at all and the ending was too unrealistic that it was just unsatisfying. Went in blind and wanting to give it a chance but was ultimately disappointed. However, the acting was good (writing not so much) and the visuals were nice."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "03f90f61-038a-43cd-b7c3-40b9dea2c256", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bafe09421359ec8d9f30d8400d4e2bc4457dc2a0536215322b20029e9569d7d8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "lopresti-46927", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "In general, the story was pretty good. It was a decent thriller with some jump, scare moments, some gruesome body stuff and a pretty good twist. It also reflected the realities of mental health and clingy relationships. I've heard some complain about the pacing towards the middle/end but in my opinion, the pacing was fine. It didn't feel drawn out and it ended exactly when it should've.\n\nThe characters themselves were pretty good. Sydney Sweeney did a decent job. She's not gonna win a Grammy for her performance, but she played her role well of the innocent but beautiful woman and has a good character arc.\n\nI really did like how they used music and different camera angles to set a very tense tone.\n\nOverall, it's in decent movie with some good tense moments and a pretty good story."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4e8c7b74-10b0-4a1e-b525-ba397af3d749", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5de3425f2f41637be12017dd55aef076d059e2ee56ce63f94973aca7af82bff8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "ChetXBuck", "rating": null, "date": "2025-12-20", "title": null, "content": "This film is good, entertaining, solid, and cheesy fun, with just enough serious and surprisingly complex storylines to appeal to both mainstream audiences and lighter film critics. It builds steadily toward a crescendo--perhaps more than one-with a handful of well-timed twists and turns that should satisfy popcorn-loving moviegoers from college age to adulthood.\n\nNone of the performances are likely to earn an Academy Award, but the cast does a credible job portraying desperate, flawed, and occasionally unhinged characters. The film is helped along by its beautiful setting, striking home, and an ensemble of attractive actors, which carry it through a few moments where the plot flirts with jumping the shark on believability.\n\nStill, enough thought and structure have gone into the screenplay to make it feel like one of the twist-heavy domestic dramas of past decades, rather than a throwaway thriller. The pacing holds, the stakes escalate,& the film largely earns its moments of excess."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e4c99073-b5e2-4feb-8c9e-9634534b3865", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d83538a302ecb52030918eb3c7c4151059b6951c00a0c621e10d39e3bf89e362"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "steiner-sam", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "It's a sort of gaslight revenge thriller set in modern times on Long Island, New York. We first meet Millie Calloway, a young woman with a checkered past, who is living in her car, applies for a maid position with the super-wealthy Winchester family. Nina (Amanda Seyfried) seems super-enthusiastic, while her handsome husband, Andrew (Brandon Sklenar) runs the business inherited from his late father. Nina and Andrew have a daughter, Cece (Indiana Elle). Andrew's snobby mother, Evelyn (Elizabeth Perkins), also appears over time. A groundskeeper, Enzo (Michele Morrone), also plays a key role.\n\nMillie is hired for the live-in maid position, but things immediately turn south due to Nina's erratic behavior, as she blames Millie for incidents she knows nothing about. Andrew, whom Nina's female friends adore, is very supportive of Millie. We learn more about Millie's and Nina's difficult backgrounds. Of course, an incident blows up into violence, with flashbacks to some earlier incidents. An empathetic police officer (Alexandra Seal) helps provide the solution.\n\n\"The Housemaid\" is a sort of thriller, because it's obvious within the first 15 minutes who the villain is. We then wait for the villain to be exposed. There are some clever plot twists, but some of the motivations for events aren't believable. As we wait for the inevitable, it almost becomes a caricature of some of the old gaslight movies. Amanda Seyfried has the most interesting role. If you want a revenge for evil behavior movie, go ahead and take it in."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "290b556b-1e4d-47eb-8aa4-9e018f5775f0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "77c5cd816dfbfe044bdf0b7a425676198566cee05e44354dfc267a516900f26b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "sukkelmatt", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-01", "title": null, "content": "While I like thriller movies, this movie just didn't have the wow factor for me. The movie started well, but the middle of the movie kinda dragged. The problem I found with this movie compared to other great murder thrillers I've watched is it didn't send shivers down my neck. Watching it sometimes felt more like a love drama movie than thriller. The violent ending I thought happened too quickly, but as the movie is based of a book maybe there are limitations.\n\nOverall, the movie was entertaining and I enjoyed the plot. The pacing and what was mentioned above is my reasons for the average score."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e628c7ff-f09a-4bc6-9b7d-fc4e511d708c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a94469c77bcde784c1eb6a7215d2078697eb247c1c7150b9da4055cf89841f36"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "DarkVulcan29", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "Millie (Sydney Sweeney) is hired by Nina Winchester (Amanda Seyfried) a rich social lite to is hired to be a housemaid, much of the surprise by her husband Andrew (Brandon Sklenar), but Millie will discover that in their household, nothing is quite what it seems.\n\nAmanda Seyfried really surprised me here, for a while I never thought of her as much has an actress, but here she proved me wrong, really keeps you on edge. Sydney Sweeney is also good, has Millie, displaying such fear and confusing quite perfectly, I believe she's a better actress then she is giving credit. Brandon Sklenar is also great as Andrew. This movie has many twists you won't see coming, just when you think how it's going to end, it pulls the rug right out from under you. My mild complaint it drags a little in spots, but other than that a well made thriller."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "78b52fb7-598f-4d41-acc2-39e4713bba8c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7545221ce0f9d93ddb6b9b0ca1ccc6dfe0087792cd658fc3a8e7528c7bdcd811"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "ag-32158", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "Though the first act feels rushed and a bit far-fetched, it pays off with a twist I didn't see coming. The intimacy is tasteful, both leads shine, and it's great to see Amanda Seyfried commanding a role she absolutely nails. I was engaged the entire film and the ending made me linger. Well-Done to the crew and cast."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7b7089f7-836b-4704-9cd5-aaafdd1d9c16", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9f1cd3329ba25af171356109157348d48b909aab9cf388ddfb6fcc4c3c7c20d4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "TheMovieLovingCorner", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "I went into this film not having read the book beforehand, so I went into it without knowing all the twists and turns. And from perspective I can say that it is a really good thriller with well executed twists and reveals The psychological aspects of the film is also really well done at making mentally tense moments carry out to the audience, making the audience experience the uncomfortable feeling of being gaslit and manipulated.\n\nThe main cast also delivers really solid performances. Amanda Seyfried and Sydney Sweeney have excellent chemistry on screen and they both play really well against each other.\n\nMy only problem with the film is Michele Morrone's character, who simply did not work for me. He felt out of place, didn't do much, and it wasn't really clear of why he was there how his character came into the picture of the plot.\n\nBut all in all this is a great film for people who like a good, well executed thriller."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "80b46fb0-312a-4f6d-b39d-7ad63e53cfe4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2985e9abc1a9fa4bc0cd91483c645be71fd7597cfa013c4f402a886ab728e110"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Apear96", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-20", "title": null, "content": "I'm not sure how closely this followed the book, but the first half of the film was genuinely fantastic. The pacing was tight, the tension worked, and it felt like it was building toward something strong. The second half, though, became redundant. Not just with the sex scenes, but with the story itself. Once Andrew is revealed as the sociopath, the thriller element completely disappears and the writing starts to feel lazy - one part being all of them jus not mentioning Chrissy anymore...\n\nAs for Sydney Sweeney, yes, she's attractive, but that can't be the entire performance. Every scene feels exactly the same emotionally. There's no range, no shift, no depth. It's frustrating to watch when there are plenty of actresses who can deliver real emotional weight while being just as compelling on screen. If Hollywood is casting her primarily for looks over talent, it shows here, and it hurts the film.\n\nOverall, a strong first act can't save a second half that loses its edge and is extremely predictable ."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cfb699e2-1a09-4af0-a746-4193845549f6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "80e7f5b0495d626fa7d905a13a357c246297749d6d5418bcdf6eaeca258b866d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "jared-25331", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-24", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid (2025) is a psychological thriller movie based on the 2022 novel of the same name directed by Paul Feig and it follows a struggling woman staring work as a housemaid for an affluent, elite couple. This is a movie that caught my eye because of Paul Feig and the cast, so I waited for it to come out and the movie was awesome.\n\nPositives for The Housemaid (2025): For a genre that I've seen so many times with the same result, I have to give Paul Feig credit for taking this genre and doing something different with it. There are some directions that I didn't see coming and I loved it because you don't get to see that from this genre. I also have to say that the cast is really good here. Of course, Sydney Sweeney is great as this struggling woman which makes no sense given who she is, but I'm not a casting director. Anyways, I like how she start off this normal woman, who is experiencing so much craziness in her front of her and then she goes insane like all of her other characters in the past. Brandon Sklenar was awesome as the husband who is basically Bruce Wayne with a different name and different characteristics, but I think it's safe to say that he is going to be Batman in the DCU. The standout of this movie was Amanda Seyfried, who is having the time of her life as the wife and I will say that this is best her performance ever. If you took me two decades ago that Karen Smith from Mean Girls (2004) was going to be a psycho wife, I would've laughed because Karen Smith was a dumbass who couldn't scare a mouse if she tried and I would've been put in my place. The movie does this thing where you think you what is going to happen and then something else happens that changes everything, while also having fun with the premise. And finally, the plot twist was genuinely shocking because I didn't see it coming at all which was nice to see from a movie in this genre.\n\nNegatives for The Housemaid (2025): The movie does go heavy on exposition with certain things and it can get annoying.\n\nOverall, The Housemaid (2025) is one of the best surprises of 2025 for me and it is one of my favorite movies of 2025."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9c131efd-70b7-4434-9b56-2331aa54087b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c6b59c83b582faf47f9e5cac50ba9fdcc19170bb6f93d9f0a6d0804f9860e55c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "filmreviewradical", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "Homeless, jobless and just released from a ten year prison sentence for manslaughter Millie (Sydney Sweeney) accepts an unexpected position as a housemaid in the wealthy Winchester household in Nassau, Long Island. The behaviour of mother of one Nina (Amanda Seyfried) then becomes increasingly erratic and abusive towards Millie at the same time as a relationship starts to develop between Millie and Nina's husband Andrew (Brandon Sklenar). Desperate not to lose her job, which carries the risk of a return to gaol, Millie is taken on a terrifying psychological rollercoaster ride in which seemingly nothing is as it first appears. Filmed in New Jersey this 2025 feature film is a psychological mystery thriller based on the novel by Freida McFadden (as adapted for the screen by the hilariously named Rebecca Sonnenshine), and directed by Paul Feig, having the same kind of twisting and turning plot as Feig's impressive 'A Simple Favour'. Visceral, contrived, at times unconvincing, more than a touch operatic, tinged with occasional humour, and extremely manipulative as a story (one of the film's main themes of course is manipulation) the film deals with a number of themes and issues including gender, class, silent hidden victims (whether through exploitation in employment or domestic partner abuse), and the socially damaging effects of the so called 'justice system' (stigma, discrimination, amongst other things) and mental health system (the common problem of misdiagnosis - and worse - by doctors). And like any good thriller of this sort it saves one of it's twists til the end, involving Andrew's mum Evelyn (Elizabeth Perkins)."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fbbfd992-0848-44b8-9d13-5d30fa474b73", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c23960eae1858bbd3a432d6b2c430986bded27c91e0476d88d8602b46ce97847"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "xydhrzrk", "rating": 3, "date": "2025-12-28", "title": null, "content": "I went into this with out reading the book, which I heard was excellent. Sadly found it predictable and poorly acted. Sydney Sweeney is lovely to look at but her acting here is dry and about as interesting as cardboard. The male character is Noxious but easy on the eyes, again,...bland and boring! The other female character is pretty good,-but jeez!-this movie is sadly overrated. The story was decent but the casting and direction was seriously lacking. Long shots of nothing, to try to add suspense, came across as self indulgent. Was really hoping for a good movie, but sadly predictable. Would have made a better movie of the week on TRU. Again, yeah.yawn."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "96184c3d-9181-4aa0-8e55-36c41f1a1549", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "df118be957fb18af4d891feb66b714d79acbc8c86031066899a7d770dfc7abae"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "virindra", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-29", "title": null, "content": "Millie Calloway, played by Sydney Sweeney, lives in her car when she gets the chance to work as a housemaid for a wealthy family. Nina Winchester, Amanda Seyfried, her husband Andrew, Brandon Sklenar and their daughter Cece seem picture perfect at first. Millie even gets her own room in the attic. By the second day on the job, it becomes clear that nothing is what it seemed.\n\nNina turns out to be a deeply unstable housewife who constantly accuses Millie of lying. Things quickly spiral out of control. What follows feels predictable on the surface. Millie starts to feel sorry for Andrew for having such a wife, and Andrew feels sorry for Millie for being blamed for things she did not do. Andrew eventually throws Nina out and files for divorce, ready to build a happy life with Millie. That is the moment when Millie realizes that everything she has experienced so far was only the beginning.\n\nI have to say, I liked this movie a lot. I read reviews claiming Sydney Sweeney cannot act, but I strongly disagree. She does a solid job here and I am looking forward to seeing her in Christy. At first I even thought the IMDb photos of Sydney and Amanda looked confusingly similar, but once the movie starts, it is immediately clear who is who. Amanda Seyfried simply has more experience and it shows. Her performance alongside Brandon Sklenar is chaotic in the best possible way and gives the film a strong thriller vibe.\n\nThe plot twists work well and the movie never bored me. Even when certain moments were predictable, the acting from all three leads was strong enough to keep me fully engaged."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a08fe9cd-da3a-4644-af7e-224f94d80ef7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "db1071211985b17b9a8605db58fbdef7fa0b2cedb689e073f2411909259f55c8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "sengelbrecht-36920", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-15", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is precisely what you think it would be: a shockingly crazy, over-the-top romantic thriller, but it does the job of being an entertaining movie on top of that. Going into it, I had low expectations that it would be good, because I was fully expecting a stupid smut movie, but this actually has some great twists and turns and well-done performances, too! Brandon Sklenar and Amanda Seyfried are both excellent here, and they do so much with their characters by showing the many sides of each. I wish the same could be said for Sydney Sweeney, though, as she is not a good actress at all, really just giving a one-note performance and terrible line readings. She doesn't do much for this movie, even though she really is the main character. But despite that, I was impressed by Paul Feig's direction. After he was known as a big television guy and for directing Melissa McCarthy movies (looking at you, Ghostbusters 2016), I thought he did a great job here. Overall, this movie is not in the top tier of 2025 in the slightest, but it is very entertaining. I think this is worth seeing as a date-night movie, and it's worth watching for the many twists and turns it takes, while also featuring some great direction and performances! 7.2/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "00f2e295-3901-4b89-b984-eca4408bb216", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "99c474b379b9e99cb1b55daae60c5ef3e37b09672860adb17736b2155f431be5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "AdamL-7981", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "Adapting a popular book is always a difficult task, and while director Paul Feig does a decent job here, the film ultimately feels like a battle between two performances.\n\nOn one side, you have Amanda Seyfried, who impresses as usual. She puts on a great performance that manages to keep the film well-grounded even when the script wobbles. On the other side, Sydney Sweeney's performance is frankly cringey. She frequently takes the viewer out of the moment, often trailing off with line reads that sound like mumbling. She has very little inflection and fails to emote, which makes the chemistry difficult to believe.\n\nStructurally, the movie is a mixed bag. The first act is a bit laughable, but it manages to build up well before getting bogged down by unnecessary exposition in the second act-it feels like the studio thought the audience needed to be spoon-fed every detail. The third act is where it loses me slightly; it veers away from the psychological thriller aspect of the book into a \"slasher\" theme. Some of these scenes feel out of place, particularly one featuring music from Kelly Clarkson that feels like it was clearly slapped on in post-production.\n\nOverall, the movie effectively delivers a solid twist that will have you thinking you missed the signs leading up to it. It is buoyed by Seyfried's amazing performance, but between the spoon-fed exposition and Sweeney's lack of range, it lands as just slightly above average."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6f9e98b7-819f-498d-a65e-15d2612270b8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ed80f0bae94f7aa6e3215dd5e98a00c77a00d25e6362452b9ab3572bd30ac881"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "DigitalH-8", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-17", "title": null, "content": "Worth the watch here. So the book is pretty good and I enjoyed that a lot so was nervous as usually these things do not go well when adapted, at least sometimes. Here though it is fairly well done and a good watch, tense and conveys the absolute nutjob characters very well.\n\nHelped along with solid performances from the two main leads, Amanda and Sydney with quite the twist that I think is pulled off quite successfully.\n\nFor sure a different type of Christmas movie. Enjoy."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4252090e-5411-425a-9365-832d9874a33b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "cca71de40a38b52fbdf3d2d3bdc8e7f8f9eb948bf3fee4e2014ffeb2408b78e3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "tobyjpegg", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-05", "title": null, "content": "January - The Housemaid Rating: 3/5 or 6/10\n\nThe Housemaid is an absolutely brilliant book by Freida McFadden. I understand that the movie is an adaptation, not a carbon copy of the book. However, I feel like a lot of the scenes were either drawn out or too short. I have several points which I am going to go through, ordered from most important to least important.\n\nANDREW LIKES IT CLEAN Throughout the movie, Andrew is shown to like everything neat and tidy, which is why in the book, when Millie leaves some books out, he lashes out and locks her in the bedroom. In the movie, Millie drops a plate and Andrew tells her not to clean it up. I know it's part of the story for him to conflict with himself, however this unintentionally conflicts with his character being the OCD-type. They clearly tried to show that Andrew likes things clean, which is why it confused me when the movie went off track and had him tell Millie to cut herself (a messy activity) instead of putting books on her belly for six hours as a form of torture. This whole storyline with Andrew being a clean guy conflicts with itself multiple times in the movie.\n\nTHE ENZO STORYLINE In the book, Enzo is explored quite deeply and we are introduced to a side plot involving how his sister was killed by a man like Andrew. He resents Andrew for a lot of the things he has done that Enzo has witnessed. This was lightly touched on in the movie, where Enzo simply tells Nina that his sister was killed by an \"Andrew-type\". I feel like this side plot could have been explored a lot deeper like the book did. In the movie, Enzo felt less like a side character and more like a background character.\n\nTHE KNIFE In the book, the plot twist was amazing. When Millie uses all of the tools Nina had given her over time to escape and trap Andrew, it felt powerful and earned. In the movie, Nina just leaves a knife in the cupboard with no buildup or other items to help her. The use of the knife is also inconsistent and unrealistic, because at the end of the movie it is revealed that the first responding police officer is the sister of Andrew's first wife who went missing. She acts like nothing happened and later dismisses the fact that there is a deep cut in his neck. This isn't realistic, because a simple autopsy would reveal the stab wound had to have been done by someone else, not to mention the missing single tooth. She also stabbed him in a lethal area, yet he survives for days.\n\nENERGY PROBLEM Somehow, all three of the main characters who were locked in the room had no visible energy loss or after-effects. Nina is somewhat excusable as she didn't suffer major physical injuries. However, Millie somehow manages to have enough energy to fight, stab, and kill a fully grown man after cutting herself deeply 21 times. Andrew also still has enough energy to fight both women and chase them around the house after being locked in a room for two to three days with severe blood loss. All characters survive on three small bottles of water with unrealistic stamina. In the book, after three days with no water, Andrew dies, which made far more sense.\n\nCONTINUITY ERRORS There were multiple continuity errors in the movie. One that I remember very vividly is when Millie (Sydney Sweeney) is arrested for stealing Nina's car. Andrew pulls up in a black Mercedes or another black car, then later drives home in Nina's white Alfa Romeo. This car isn't a taxi, as he was the one driving it, and it's also never shown again in the movie. Nina drives an Alfa Romeo and Andrew drives a Range Rover; these are shown in multiple front driveway shots throughout the movie, including shots with Millie's car.\n\nTHE LANDSCAPER MYSTERY In the book, it is summer or spring time (hence the need for a landscaper). For some reason, the Winchesters have a landscaper (Enzo) during the winter, while snow is covering the grass and plants. We don't really see a point to Enzo being there, and it feels strange. Him appearing in the window (which causes Millie to drop Andrew's grandma's Chinese pottery) was completely unneeded. It felt like a cheap jump scare, as if they were trying to make Enzo look like the villain or the creepy guy. In the book, he is mysterious and barely speaks English, however in the movie he does not stutter once.\n\nPOOR ACTING Sydney Sweeney is known for one major thing (I'll let you figure that out), and it feels like not many people focus on her acting. Either way, her portrayal of Millie in this movie was very weak. The forced stutters were unnecessary, and when they could have been useful, they weren't added.\n\nTHE HUMOUR There's a difference between making light of a bad situation and making weak jokes about domestic violence. The book is serious and meant to create fear and awareness. The movie attempts humour in dark scenes that could have been psychologically terrifying. The main example is when Millie locks Andrew in the room and says, \"I need a sandwich.\" This felt out of place, unfunny, and tone-deaf.\n\nTHE SWEARING I don't mind swearing in movies; I think it can add realism and character depth. However, the F-word was massively overused in this movie, especially in the scenes where Millie is locked in the room talking to Andrew through the door.\n\nTHE PEANUT BUTTER REFERENCE In the book, Millie serves, eats, or buys peanut butter (I can't fully remember). She is then told off by Nina because Cecilia is allergic to peanut butter. This was never explored or proven in the movie. However, there was one hint when Millie goes to the cinema room to get a snack and watch TV. There were Reese's Pieces in the cupboard she grabbed the snack from, which was a cool Easter egg that was almost definitely done on purpose.\n\nTHE BEDROOM This is a personal opinion, so take it lightly. Millie's room looks far too big and fancy. In the book, it is described as a closet-sized room with a bed, bookcase, and cupboard. In the movie, the room was too clean, large, and comfortable, and it didn't feel like a traumatic place to be locked in for days.\n\nFINAL THOUGHTS Overall, the movie was weak in many areas, but for an adaptation rather than a carbon copy, it did fairly well. I would assume it didn't have a huge budget, given the lack of top-level celebrities.\n\nNina's performance was good, but there was room for improvement.\n\nMillie's acting was poor.\n\nAndrew could have been portrayed as far more evil."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3fcff930-580d-4bfb-9d89-c5f67da92ede", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a507539324801ea1dfa9278748a5f7900a20861f9763a19fb249edc419d427c5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "GaiusL", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "This movie is perfect in many ways, it can be very suspenseful, very bloody, and overall just a great thriller. Amanda's performance should give her an Oscar. Sydneys performance as Millie wasn't the greatest but she still deserves some recognition. I would give this movie an extra 5 points for how Amanda's was but I can't give it a 15."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3ab7611f-a96c-417e-940a-0baf5621016c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f9bc408abdc3b262a37dd07f7892f6842f517c90926a7ea7ac81a66c2f6dc97e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "jgcorrea", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-03", "title": null, "content": "The more I think about this film, the more dissatisfied I am with it. While seeing it, I was at first annoyed at the passivity of Millie (the maid of the title), then suspicious that I wasn't getting all the facts. This played out with the change of viewpoints midway through the movie, coming at the situation from the wife's point of view. Okay, twists are cool. But from both points of view, the actions were waaaaaaaaay over the top, and when Millie finally grows a backbone, her change from victim to avenger is right up there on the \"Oh, come on\" meter, particularly when her backstory comes out. Then they pull a deus ex machina to tie up all the plot noodles and still leave one hanging for a sequel. (Several sequels probably, actually.)"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c0ea80ca-7240-4fc2-85a0-2585089e55f1", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bbd13eb7b73b86f637d6edb276bd0443efae7ca0a40feac31d40883056906a8a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Kristina_vonsel", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-15", "title": null, "content": "There are near to none loose ends here... The housemaid is a brilliant masterpiece that will tell us more than one story of defiance and defeat, recilliance and redemption.\n\nMillie, Nina and Andrew revolve around each other in this insanely clever and assumingly simple plot, but hang on and pay attention. The devil is in the detail.\n\nEnjoy!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "71081776-91c5-4e40-a11f-bee45492213f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b944aaac37d608588b720e35ff4409b4c84a40445478fc9ee86cb555c554cb5d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "margaritakor-63497", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-11", "title": null, "content": "The movie is being underrated by the critics. The plot was very clever and made you wonder what will happen next. There was a nice twist in the plot that you weren't expecting it. It kept you focused till the end with excitement and agony. It is definitely one of the best to it's genre at least from this decade. Totally worth watching!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8e6df3bc-693e-4a12-89bc-931150520045", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2f400417f855744104291ac2463c9d03a743255e15544c1f277552d62ff11520"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "blackledgec", "rating": 3, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "Felt the need to review this film as it annoyed me too much not to.\n\nThis film's plot was specifically designed for the audience watching it. And as such ruins any realism it could have had. I came away from it feeling like I'd been cheated by a con artist. There were too many role reversals going on, too many inconsistencies and a lack of focusing on certain characters that I won't mention as this review will be spoiler free.\n\nIt bordering a made for TV movie. I don't recommend it to anyone who gets annoyed by too much audience spoon-feeding."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ac0a4e4b-2313-4020-9134-8e13c0e9fb6f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "befe7b9c698f951639da9efd6e5754c06046b1d140735bdfd434e4b70a8c181f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Allnoir_ovthings", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-28", "title": null, "content": "They finally played into Sydney's strong suits, which we all know what they are, but her acting was actually pretty good here.\n\nThe first half was definitely the strong half, and going into this film I had no knowledge and I was for sure expecting a supernatural horror element but I was pleasantly surprised when there wasn't. It was just pure control, manipulation, and psychosis.\n\nAs for the twist in the second half, it was great, but I thought they spent way too much time harping on the backstory and the twist itself and the movie started to drag a bit.\n\nAnd as for the ending, really? So she just happens to apply for a job with a women in the exact situation? Or is the theme here that rich men are abusers? 6/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e0637f89-32bc-496f-895b-084a149da4fa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "58b787d3d40b6f60339fb1ac2cba776b664659a10d1a34204365667ca187cdc8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "km37_37", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-03", "title": null, "content": "Saw this in theatre with my mom 12/27/2025. Was definitely more explicit than the book with the hotel scene (Sydney Sweeney full frontal). The gore may be a bit much for some people. Otherwise, it matched the book well excluding few details such as Nina being plus sized and Cecelia having a peanut allergy (which at least isn't addressed). I wish it would've gone deeper into Enzo's character as the book did, but added details like Cece's dollhouse was quite wonderful. I enjoyed the changed ending compared to the book as well and thought the change in punishments was done smoothly. Cast was very fitting besides Nina, but her actress did a wonderful job expressing emotions and acting for the character. She was made a bit more likable than in the book which helped the audience to not entirely dislike her character I feel. Shots were done beautifully."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1b3596b9-5e1b-4b84-a722-5e29a79fc3dd", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e9d0aaa772ee97cc552284b55bb02307d0e6ccecbdda9ab8c401ce2ce6b318aa"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Binkconn", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-16", "title": null, "content": "With a cast that definitely won't be rocking the dreidel in Yiddish theater anytime soon, Paul Feig moves from his traditional wheelhouse of brilliant female-led comedies to more glossy Lifetime movie avenues in his adaptation of Freida McFadden's thriller about a young ex-con ('hardest working actor of the year going by movie count' Sydney Sweeney) who seeks employment with a wealthy wife (Amanda 'don't invest in her blood-testing company' Seyfried) but finds a web of mind-games and deceptions waiting behind the freshly-scrubbed Elantras, chiseled hubbies, Stepford parties and Gen Z Martha Stewart veneers. Feig cosplays the paranoia well and it's a decent enough distraction from the holiday shopping rush, in-laws, etc., but I still think Sydney's boxing biopic \"Christy\" was overlooked as a stronger if more down-market portrayal of domestic abuse (though the critics completely shut out my favorite of the year \"Anniversary\" in favor of Leo sweating and squinting in a pancho for three hours, so what do I know). But in a holiday season that just took an incredibly darker turn maybe \"The Housemaid\" will take on an increased relevance for those curious about what goes on behind the closed doors of the rich and seemingly happy. Anything including \"Avatar: Fire, Ash, And The Insurance Lawsuit Liability\" are welcome distractions. Ho ho ho and Oy yoi yoi. RIP the great Rob Reiner and his wife Michele."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "450a6d7f-32b6-4eae-a703-b6c3ba8ec43b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d58b65afacf8892f57813cdca766ae5011c042f559e2c4fbe22cbf589ca604b9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "cinemapersonified", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-14", "title": null, "content": "Rating - 6.0: Overall, this movie is saved by its second half being genuinely entertaining, as Amanda Seyfried shows why she is a good actress by entirely carrying this movie on her back, having to pick up the pieces of Sydney Sweeney's bad acting, unnatural dialogue, and BookTok-style filmmaking.\n\nDirection - Decent: The direction on a macroscale feels like a white woman's BookTok mystery; The direction on a microscale feels incredibly forced, especially when Sydney Sweeney is acting; The storytelling is surprisingly good, as the whole second half is very interesting and entertaining and makes up for the mishaps in the first half, but the movie does not stick the landing with its formulaic climax and forced ending; Tension is manufactured artificially but does help make this movie feel like a thriller at moments\n\nStory - Pretty Bad: The concept is a little all over the place, as the movie tries to be something at the start but totally flips its narrative at the halfway mark, with the second half being way more entertaining than the first; The plot structure is a bit of a mess with how the movie is structured into two halves, but the second half is more entertaining and allows Amanda Seyfried to show why she is a good actress; The ending for this movie sets up an unnecessary sequel that makes the movie's important message feel campy; Character writing is pretty forced and shallow\n\nScreenplay - Bad: The dialogue is so bad and unnatural that it made me cringe at so many moments, especially when Sydney Sweeney speaks; The humor is somewhat present, as it does elevate the entertainment a bit; The symbolism is decent in the grand scheme of things but feels very forced and only becomes relevant towards the end; The foreshadowing is a key component of this movie, as there is a shift at the halfway point, and it does a good job of keeping the audience on their toes and making them surprised by what happens next\n\nActing - Pretty Bad to Decent: Sydney Sweeney - Bad (My god is this one of the most emotionless and toneless performances I have ever seen; Sweeney shows no range whatsoever as almost all of her expessions feel unnatural and not how humans would react to things; her chemistry with the other characters feels forced and unnatural; the only thing going for Sweeny throughout this movie is she is actively trying to distract you from her bad acting), Amanda Seyfried - Good (The real only saving grace for this movie as she shows why she is an actually good actress; she shows a lot of range in her character, especially in the second half when she is given more material to work with; without giving anything away, her character is the true focal point for the movie and makes up for the bad aspects of this movie that it actually makes you empathize with her character; while her chemistry with Sklenar is fine and her chemistry with Sweeney is a bit forced, her performance really is a one-woman show as she has to carry this entire movie on her back and she does a good job with it), Brandon Sklenar - Decent (He would have been such a bigger actor in the late 2000s as that was a time-period where looks and charisma alone could get you jobs; however, his performance is fine and he does have an entertaining character; the chemistry he has with the two leads is a bit forced but fine), Rest of the cast - Pretty Bad (Typical Booktok style acting)\n\nScore - Decent: The score helps establish the tone and tension, even though it can feel a bit manufactured\n\nSoundtrack - Decent: The soundtrack feels very catered to a white woman audience on BookTok\n\nCinematography - Decent: The cinematography feels very much like a white woman's BookTok movie but is used to help establish tension in the thriller elements; It also feels like many of the shots are just to establish this lavish house\n\nEditing - Decent: The editing style feels very much like a white woman's BookTok movie, but it is used to help establish tension in the thriller elements\n\nSound - Decent: Sound is used to artificially manufacture tension and make this feel more like a thriller\n\nProduction Design - Pretty Good: The old-money style house shows the world the housemaid is entering, as their wealth acts as a plot point for what Seyfried and Sweeney's characters desire\n\nCostumes - Decent: The costumes showcase how rich this community is, but many of the clothes Sydney Sweeney wears are very unrealistic for a housemaid, with Seyfried even calling this out in the movie, as it looks like she is wearing them to distract from her bad acting\n\nPacing - The pacing is a bit slow in the first half but moves at the right pace in the second half\n\nClimax - The climax is a bit formulaic for a BookTok thriller, and the ending sets up a sequel that feels completely unnecessary\n\nTone - The tone is very much that of a white woman's BookTok thriller."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ce87c576-cc24-4d8b-b2f4-a4fdb2a0f22a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "83d18aed966d18c1e300a71363d50ff841449da8713f4e3bc2522ae0cd2b4a77"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "kosmasp", "rating": 9, "date": "2026-01-20", "title": null, "content": "No pun intended - I did not read the book(s) before watching this. So I have no idea how close this is to the adaptation of the source material. Judging from the reviews and the score it seems that people approve generally speaking.\n\nHaving the two female actresses doing their thing and playing off each other is quite genius. You will be guessing what is going on and where this is heading. Well again if you have not read what this is based on. Sydney is not going to disappoint neither is Amanda or anyone else in this movie.\n\nRead as little as possible (review wise, no pun intended once again), so you get the most out of this ..."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2984e985-9af9-49d2-b0fa-d5d239db5728", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4302485c3250387b74c6d1469de3e35ed86dfb66ad8613238da9a3c208d52cb9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "FlorinB4", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-29", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid feels like a forgettable Sunday movie, nothing special, nothing memorable. It tries to be shocking, but the story is flat and the pacing drags. I was honestly bored for large parts of it. The fact that the only thing people seem to remember involves a sexual moment with a famous actor says everything about how empty the rest of the film is. Another reminder that movies just aren't made like they used to."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cc96ac6b-23ca-41e7-9cff-6368da6cd62f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "32ded25a097ae960262c20dc5850e134454e1a6b8ec80c1f4f70a4d306b970f3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "nickcrowell5", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "Good movie based on a good book. I've read the source material and I still felt myself on the edge of my seat and gripping my pearls at this one. It's sexy, suspenseful, and smart. Everyone deserves a raise for bringing it on screen. Amanda Seyfried in particular had me shooketh. The one liners they were throwing out left and right were great. I need more books adapted from Freida McFadden."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9df64243-9b13-4902-a1bc-2f500e068f66", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "848661b7ebab0d62ffecd901daaf855155969b2dadeb48e7ebc7cea1f768474f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "darkreignn", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-26", "title": null, "content": "I don't particularly think that Sydney Sweeney is the best actress on the face of the earth, but her recent films have been unabashedly entertaining - \"Anyone But You,\" \"Eden,\" and \"Immaculate\" were all a lot of fun, and with \"The Housemaid\" looking like another schlocky thriller, I was genuinely looking forward to giving it a go, especially with the inclusion of Amanda Seyfried who is truly a phenomenal actress. I found myself watching this in a completely full theatre, which surprised me; I've not read the book this film was based on, but if my auditorium was anything to go by, it seems to be popular. And after watching this movie I can see why because \"The Housemaid\" was a very good time at the movies.\n\nSydney Sweeney plays Millie Calloway, a meek and mild woman who is so down on her luck that she finds herself living in her car. Applying for job after job, she finally lucks out after getting accepted to be a housemaid for the wealthy Winchester family. Amanda Seyfried plays Nina Winchester, a seemingly sweet woman whose initial niceness is so extreme that one could easily see why any man - in this case Andrew Winchester, played by Brandon Sklenar - would want to marry her. However, the longer Millie is employed at the Winchester residence, the more bizarre things get as facades fall away and truth bubbles to the surface.\n\nWhat follows is a very entertaining popcorn flick that combines aspects of romantic thrillers and more traditional, pulpy psychological thrillers. On one hand you have \"The Housemaid\" flirting heavily with \"forbidden fruits,\" for lack of a better phrase; there's a constant undercurrent of want in this movie - wanting safety, stability, affection, validation, and of course, wanting something or someone that one can't have. There are longing glances, power imbalances, emotional manipulation, and an uneasy tension that comes from desire being weaponized. All of this gives the film a faintly romantic sheen, even as things are clearly going off the rails where attraction and danger start to blur together. I really enjoyed this part of the film and honestly found myself swooning.\n\nOn the other hand, the movie is very much a straightforward thriller, content to lean into secrets, reversals, and escalating paranoia. There's a soap-opera-esque quality to the storytelling that works in its favor, at least for me. The movie becomes totally ridiculous and unbelievable, akin to something you'd expect to see on daytime TV or in cheesy CW dramas, but man is it so much fun to watch as things continue to spiral.\n\nThis tonal balancing act won't work for everyone, especially if you're expecting something a bit more mature or elevated, but I found it surprisingly effective. \"The Housemaid\" knows exactly what kind of movie it is: a glossy, slightly trashy, thriller that plays best when you surrender to it and when you stop trying to categorize it too neatly and just let it entertain you. And entertain it does."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "26e5c8a7-ef97-4cc6-b134-8bad304b5e12", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "9d42c03cdeee6dab652869c8905a9148a2027f7c085112d5fada26beb6c70772"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "TheNamelessCzar", "rating": 4, "date": "2025-12-27", "title": null, "content": "I don't understand the good reviews. Well, I guess I do. People like to go to the movies for an escape and some mindless entertainment. The crowd I watched it with in the theater sure was engrossed and enthralled. But that's the problem with this film. It's completely mindless. It makes no sense whatsoever. The plot holes are humongous, and the plot is predictable. You can see the ending coming a mile away. And the writing is horrible. I know movies are fantasy, but at least try to write characters that act like human beings would act in these situations. If all the characters acted like people normally would, the movie would be over in 15 minutes. It's implausible, contrived, and a joke. Dust this mess into the trash."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6c01f64c-cc9c-410c-955c-d663c025b3de", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c2e64ca737d50490b3c68e3147a6b4dd003607513fa6b4acc62c8760bf419391"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "rkaden-28150", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-30", "title": null, "content": "I'm a big fan of Freda McFadden and read all her books. The Housemaid series was the best and I was thrilled to hear they made this movie. Overall I thought it was good but, as with so many book to movies, why the changes in the story line and ending? Nothing was wrong with the book ending! I'm never sure why screenplay writers feel this need to make changes but it happens all too often. That being said, I did enjoy the movie. The cast was great and the story caught me from the start just as the book did. The three lead actors are not hard to look at either!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1f7f7ace-dfa6-42d9-8515-c0d81e1669fb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "681dec207af1ca2e4d28b777cdd7f3c70384123beee6795e2dd95bc8d1ee5a6a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "CSRb4u", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-31", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is an uneven psychological thriller that shows flashes of smart direction but struggles to find tonal consistency. Director Paul Feig plants visual clues early-most notably the spiral staircase and the maid's request to alter her room-that cleverly pay off in the climax, adding structural cohesion and thematic intent.\n\nHowever, the first half feels rushed and awkwardly staged, leaning too heavily on sensationalism rather than suspense. The film only begins to resemble a proper thriller in its latter half, where tension, twists, and narrative momentum finally take hold.\n\nPerformances are mixed. Amanda Seyfried stands out as the film's anchor, delivering a layered portrayal that shifts convincingly from instability to vulnerability. Sydney Sweeney is divisive-effective in conveying fear and confusion for some, but emotionally flat for others. Brandon Sklenar's performance is inconsistent, weakening the film's central menace.\n\nWhile the film explores domestic abuse within wealthy, outwardly perfect households-a subject handled with surprising resonance-it often undercuts its impact with campy execution and gratuitous scenes. Fans of the source novel may find the adaptation lacking in depth, though the film's ending arguably improves upon the book's conclusion.\n\nOverall, The Housemaid is a flawed but occasionally engaging throwback thriller: unpredictable, sometimes effective, but ultimately falling short of its source material and full potential."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "efe67bd9-d4e8-47b8-8b0c-90ff5376a5ee", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8fce93f95f2b0dbedc2cfed87c6721905eea0768364603f22f9a08c601377be0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "FeastMode", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "I found The Housemaid to be enjoyable in a one-time-viewing kind of way. The story is interesting and I was never bored. But I also wasn't wowed at all. No aspect excels. It's somewhat predictable. The middle portion drags a bit without much story progression or escalation. And the conclusion is only mildly satisfying.\n\nI know that's a lot of negatives, but I still found it entertaining.\n\n(1 viewing, 12/22/2025)"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fe482154-e001-4369-8a64-3b7ca77f4201", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1f9b84a45482ebad9c3cf693234ffef933fe840449c32ff6f41a448b0dcb3c12"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "liznbailey", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-20", "title": null, "content": "You know when you read the book and then already know that the movie is probably not as good? Not the case! This movie followed the book pretty well!!! There were a few variations but it was executed in a manner that was interesting and they did a great job! The twists and turns in the book were fun to see on the big screen."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "750c52ff-fd5a-41f1-bf76-e4fd68389352", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1094e1b42e3efee03ad5dcfdbe77aeb05d9b30d78095be154518d088a7de09d0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "deesirius", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-11", "title": null, "content": "Once again, I found myself among the few friends who didn't read the book(s)-and honestly, that worked completely in my favor. Unlike them, I went in with zero expectations, and unlike them, I enjoyed it so much more because of it.\n\nPeople often forget that it's called an adaptation for a reason-it's not meant to be a word-for-word copy of the book. While I understand how missing context or altered scenes can be frustrating for readers, those changes are often necessary to translate the story effectively from page to screen and heighten the drama.\n\nNone of that took away from the movie for me. That said, I'm not entirely convinced Sydney Sweeney was the right choice for Millie. I've also heard that Amanda Seyfried wasn't the ideal pick for Nina-but unfortunately, Amanda acted circles around Sydney, and that imbalance was my biggest issue.\n\nAs for Brandon Sklenar, they absolutely nailed that casting. They knew exactly what they were doing putting him in the role of Andrew.\n\nI fell for him the same way Millie did, while my friends sat there watching me, watching it all unfold!\n\nOverall, this was a fun watch. Nothing Oscar-worthy, but a solid romance-cough thriller? Horror??-that kept me entertained. These are the kinds of movies that are great to see in theaters: easy, engaging, edge-of-your-seat entertainment.\n\nHopefully they make the second one. Which...i might also NOT read!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9f04f65d-92ea-4063-b38e-38f71b7dab5d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ae1402d17eb38a6724cdc9e477928a5502e55d2892404faaf60a00d4fd2b7f0a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Em012", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-19", "title": null, "content": "Amanda's performance showed her true potential that she has as an actress - her acting was an art piece itself. It was raw, it was believable, it was brilliant.\n\nSometimes I had a feeling the movie itself lacks a little more in the background (e.g.: Enzo in the terrace door standing in the way he was). On top of that I felt like the transition to Amanda's story was a little too quick to be revealed.\n\nI appreciated how the film highlights manipulation between genders and the persistent lack of equality in what is considered acceptable behavior for men women. It effectively shows that attitudes we often think belong to the distant past are, in reality, still very much present today."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e37b7ccb-e7eb-4f55-ae12-09032d1dbb98", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "35717ae08cfdcd530e02348eade0c5961d8cd30f3d455adcc8a42bc271b04527"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "vengeance20", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "So, I saw this advertised while going to see Die, My Love & found it looked interesting & good. Given I have a bit of a thing for Sydney Sweeney & used to have a thing for Amanda Seyfried, I knew I had to watch for those reasons too.\n\nHoping for a fresh start, a young woman becomes a live-in maid for a wealthy couple who harbour sinister secrets.\n\nI found the film to be alright. It's above average & enjoyable, but it has pacing issues, is overly long & lacks in drama for it to be entertaining enough. The cast do well with their roles & there's plenty of eye candy with the women (Sydney Sweeney especially, bits fist!), & the drama & bits of action were good too.\n\nThe story is interesting & the twist was good also. But the film is too long 2 hours & 5 minutes (125 minutes) & has some pacing issues particularly near the end which I felt dragged on & on for the sheer sake of it. The film near the end came off as a bit preachy I think & of course when I saw who directed this, I wasn't surprised...\n\nThe films ending is good & hints at a sequel. If it means seeing more of Sydney Sweeney then count me in, however, if there is a sequel, it should be shorter, faster paced & less preachy. The film was enjoyable, but not without its faults.\n\nOverall, it's a decent flick. But not as good as made out. Give it a watch, but don't expect too much.\n\n6/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d6b3a997-4b0d-4099-a0fe-e7cf6194bd04", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "09024fa0e41ccb2d375b3a3f053c8963f45fe3a272f3d6909e027147eddd7ef7"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "adele-61115", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-20", "title": null, "content": "This is a unique story with many twists and turns! It will keep you guessing all the way until the last minute of the movie. Even thought it was long, there were no fillers or dead spaces. It kept my interest all throughout. I didn't read the book so I went completely blind and it didn't disappoint! Just when you thought you knew who the 'bad guy' was it would turn to someone else. I don't want to give much in the review because the beauty of thrillers is to know as little as possible."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "62d61015-c1d6-40cf-91eb-b3b8e068290c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "443d5c493d5606174336e1f6bcfc2182594167b878e02a231354e634569ea774"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "fluffchop", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-03", "title": null, "content": "Just saw this at the cinema in Frankston Australia. I enjoyed the movie. It felt quite long. It was well paced and an interesting set of twists and setups.\n\nI've never heard of Sydney Sweeney. She was quite good in it however her diction isn't that good sometimes.\n\nAmanda Seyfried was very accomplished in this. She's got those acting chops you'd expect from someone her age. I've always liked her in things and in this she was great.\n\nIf you like intense thrillers with a psychological edge you'll probably really like this."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "17fd7524-d80a-44e7-92ac-1399da25944e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "83f181977c27fae4df0ea1c7063af58db143328594c1e3c0e31c1d6fede7c98a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "carringtonkayno", "rating": 4, "date": "2025-12-20", "title": null, "content": "The plot was okay for most of the movie but the script was extremely weak and the acting performance was even worse. Particularly by Ms. Sweeney. It's like she doesn't even want to be an actor. The movie relied heavily on making sure her breasts were in every single scene to make up for her soulless performance. Not just by her but by the entire cast. The nude scene wasn't even enough to save this movie. And the ending requires you to completely ignore all of reality."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "69f66877-11ae-453b-b0fc-8f58bdabe1bf", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "809a50460cf593424d6966823b3e229fca2bebfe1b0543329f9c7e22144edef1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "DBC1899", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-07", "title": null, "content": "I would call this movie a dark comedy rather than a thriller. The first 30 minutes were promising and then it went off the rails for me. Amanda Seyfried is the only good thing about this movie. Sweeney's character was awkward (was that the point?). If you've read the book you'll realize they missed out on some detail that could have made the movie a lot better. 6/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "84b58950-0073-49e4-b1a4-8ce922396f8e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f789fe7d70b181233989e8ddc392316091cf45b4ba2e483d9236975ee367a6f4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "redban02", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "I went to see The Housemaid on 12/22/2025 at the theaters. I think it's highly watchable.\n\nBasically, I think there are 2 main positives. The first is that the movie is simply not boring. The pacing is great; the story is engrossing. I never yawned or found my mind drifting off at any time. If all you want is a solid popcorn flick to pass a couple hours, this movie will get the job done.\n\nThe other big upside is that Amanda Seyfried gives an excellent performance: she is quite impressive with her delivery and facial expressions, as she deftly alternates from sweet and friendly to crazy and terrifying. Her performance is the one complex and nuanced role in the whole movie, and she nails it.\n\nThat aside -- the movie doesn't rise from watchable to exceptional. Although the plot might be engrossing, many details are so farfetched and, at times, downright nonsensical. There are several plot holes and/or goofs. Actions by certain characters are puzzling or unrealistic ... For examples: the whole character named Enzo feels contrived and forced into the story. Characters get locked in an attic that seemingly has the world's most indestructible wooden door. The finale includes an eyerollingly-remarkable coincidence involving a cop.\n\nThere's some weak narration at times. I didn't find any character to be likable. They could have done more with the little girl in the household\n\nAnd last, but definitely not least -- Sweeney and Sklenar are bad actors. Sklenar, I guess, could get a break because he at least looks the part, with his hulking physique and good looks. But Sweeney's acting is atrocious. In the finale, she acts more like she's drunk when she's supposed to be fatigued. She is not convincing as a hardened parolee. And her enunciation is so bad; she kinda mumbles a bit (which becomes a big deal when her character narrates some parts)\n\n6.5/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "19af3c9a-6526-48f3-b699-4ff6026fb8ba", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6199241476560331e9e3970d2acd049de1d0060d51e250ddc14dbc869aa485ce"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "saolivaresm", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "Paul Feig returns to action in a genre he's making his own in an interesting way. This time he adapts Freida McFadden's novel with a screenplay by Rebecca Sonnenshine, resulting in a decent film that, despite its inconsistencies, proves to be a good way to pass the time.\n\nStarring Sydney Sweeney, Amanda Seyfried, Brandon Sklenar and Michele Morrone, the story takes us to the Winchester house and all the secrets hidden behind its door.\n\nThe Housemaid largely delivers on its promise, offering the intensity and tension of its two leads, who carry the film on their shoulders. Amanda Seyfried stands out, unsettling the audience with her character and imbuing it with a hidden darkness in her acting; she impresses with nuance and commitment, achieving a powerful and effective performance. Sidney Sweeney is also solid, reaffirming her status as an effective actress. Although her character occasionally borders on overacting, this isn't entirely her fault, as she shines brightly in the final act. Rather, it's certain tonal choices by the director that somewhat limit the darkness present in the novel.\n\nThis is where we move on to the screenplay, which opts for a slightly less intense approach than the novel, but is just as effective. The film's tone also helps it maintain a coherent trajectory. It has less dark and intense moments, but balances them with more dynamic and imaginative scenes that allow us, as viewers, to grasp certain messages. In this arena, Paul Feig finds a genre in which he feels very comfortable and handles it skillfully, building sensuality, compelling decisions, and a clear message about the true underlying themes of his film.\n\nIt's an imperfect film, certainly, and you may like it more or less depending on what you see, but it's by no means a bad film. Its flaw lies in trying to force certain elements that perhaps don't quite fit together, although what it does well, it achieves with great intensity. It's quite entertaining and focuses its strength on its two leads, though the rest of the cast supports it without being out of place.\n\nIt may not stand out among similar films, but The Housemaid earns its own place as a worthwhile and interesting spectacle. A sordid game between Sydney and Amanda that ultimately becomes a guilty pleasure to kick off 2026."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "dff97b95-3ae5-41e3-aa09-4c781ff0b8b2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "39d2b2860515b229784f437cf6fc386f0220356e4e65c7e03cadc4fbe997aaab"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "swvnsvm", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "10/10. The Housemaid succeeds because it stays remarkably faithful to the book while elevating the story through its performances and atmosphere. The film captures the same psychological tension, manipulation, and slow unraveling that made the novel so gripping, and the adaptation respects the twists rather than rushing or softening them. The casting is absolutely perfect-each actor embodies their character exactly as imagined on the page, and the performances add layers of unease, vulnerability, and menace that deepen the story. The acting sells every power shift, every quiet threat, and every shocking turn, making the twists hit just as hard as they did in the book. It's a rare adaptation that understands its source material and enhances it, delivering a suspenseful, unsettling, and emotionally charged experience from start to finish."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "03454486-f0f5-4612-bc5c-86f300893719", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6cd1e93c4a9c2018c700e2c7c4d14a046cc34059ced6d0caec02af2e67af8004"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "caitlincaitlin-53266", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-06", "title": null, "content": "Even though it was quite predictable, this was overall an enjoyable movie. I've not read the book and knew nothing about the premise going into it, however I saw the twist coming quite early on.\n\nThe strongest aspect of the movie was Seyfried's acting, who absolutely killed it with her character 'Nina'. I was very impressed with her abilities and was immersed in the movie for every scene she was in. In contrast, I found Sweeney to be the weakest part of the movie, coming across quite monotone and flat. Her portrayal of Millie lacked substance and it made the movie less enjoyable overall. I would have given this film a higher rating than 7 were it not for her lacklustre performance, which was so dull that it was distracting."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6842175d-e90d-4092-9889-301df9f62092", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5c281988847729dad21534dfd8104aa2d9b00b18ff243de90a25ce37157ce1f1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "Weird-O-Rama", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "This movie is based on my favorite book, and it's rare these days not to feel let down by adaptations.\n\nI think fans will be happy, as it sticks extremely close to the original story.\n\nPleasantly surprised by the acting as well.\n\nThe plot is wild; if you liked Gone Girl, you'll enjoy this. Go in blind, and you're in for a ride!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bd460d5e-2526-4cf3-bbe3-fffe567d3533", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eb597cdf375311b90ab2d5613727a4317e3c9205d0d9b10b675359176c0ee4d4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "CharlesD-25", "rating": null, "date": "2026-01-05", "title": null, "content": "ZERO mOSTEL DIDN'T KNOW THE HALF OF IT.\n\nApparently,money can't buy mental stability,either before or after the main event is over. Be warned that the second half of the film is outright gruesome==and a big switch from a first half that depends mostly on dialogue for its shivers.\n\nI keep watching the little girl,the only unsullied person in the whole thing--you hope SHE turned out to be all right!!brava to Alexandra Seal,who plays the policewoman at the end of the picture.\n\nAnd Elizabeth perkins as the Mother-In-Law---her last line at the funeral suggests her son never stood a snowball's chance since birth.\n\nHey,can i have the leftovers? There's aways way too much food sitting on the counter--why let it go to waste?"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c61d3419-0fcb-46c3-bbe4-ce637737dfa2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3e9ed6e0c560886a1569d5438e89a7f0b7742295c97dd97c3543a348d5cfc884"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "gallmann-38827", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "Referring to some of the reviews:\n\n\n* It's obvious within the first 15 minutes who the villain is\n\n\nAs a film lover and enthusiast, I completely disagree. Otherwise, I must be dumb.\n\nFor me, it was not obvious. My suspicion headed in a different direction.\n\n\n* gaps and the unfortunate lack of substance for supporting characters\n\n\nThere are no gaps or a lack of substance. It had a coherent course of events and well-developed characters. I never got bored and was entertained til the end.\n\n\n* It feels campy and cheesy for much of the runtime\n\n\nImo not at all. And believe me, I smell cheesy (or campy) from miles away. I am so on alert when it comes to this.\n\n\n* The film overall was bleh\n\n\nNope. It was not.\n\n\n* What a twist - review was rated 28 helpful out of 25 opposing\n\n\nReviews like this make me hesitate to watch. I think, WoW, twists are the best, and then I see that 25 people disagree with 28. Nevertheless, I'm glad I gave it a chance. And there was a twist, indeed.\n\n\n* A rating of 4 out of 10 states: The disastrous climax ruins whatever goodwill the film builds along the way\n\n\nRegarding disastrous - seriously? The word itself should only be used for really awful movies. This one is not. In this case, it refers to the climax. I couldn't disagree more. As a movie lover, I'm very sensitive to cheesiness and endings/conclusions. In fact, during the ending, I expected the movie to end at any moment, as I often experience with many other movies. Which would have been okay (not overwhelming, but okay) because of the satisfying conclusion. But here, it went on a few more moments, which I felt was more than just a satisfying ending. I'm trying to avoid spoilers, so I'll just say that what happened at the end could have been the final scene, as in many other movies. That would have been okay because of the twist. But here, it went on for a few more scenes, offering little nuances that I appreciated. It just felt good because it offered a few tiny extras. This film might not be a 10, but it deserves recognition for its effort to add a few more scenes at the end, which made it richer.\n\nTo be clear, besides the good ending, the whole film is worth watching.\n\n\n* A rating of 6 out of 10 states: somewhat predictable /the conclusion is only mildly satisfying\n\n\nAgain - imo it's not predictable, and the conclusion is not only not mildly satisfying but even more than that.\n\nI give it a 7 out of 10 and can definitely recommend it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "24763871-e1ce-471b-b576-c437a3de7885", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "48efaddf638c5dbdbda4681665a695e64744f3b99e9f11c0b663660d4b0505b5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "jacquesvanzyl-75383", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-23", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid doesn't just clean house-it dusts off expectations, mops the floor with clich\u00e9s, and polishes tension to a high shine. With spotless performances and a squeaky-clean script hiding dirty secrets, this ten-star thriller leaves you swept away long after the final wipe-down.\n\nFrom the very first sweep of its opening moments, The Housemaid proves that sometimes the dirtiest secrets aren't hidden under the rug-they are the rug.\n\nThis is the kind of film that invites you in politely, offers you a cup of tea, and then quietly rearranges the furniture of your expectations while you're not looking. By the time you realise what kind of house you've stepped into, you're already hooked, keys handed over, and fully prepared to stay.\n\nWhat elevates The Housemaid to five-star territory is its remarkable confidence. The film never rushes, never over-explains, and never underestimates its audience. Instead, it builds tension with patience and precision, letting atmosphere do as much work as dialogue. Every scene feels intentional, layered with subtle glances, pauses, and unspoken power dynamics that make the story simmer rather than boil over. It's a masterclass in restraint, where silence can feel louder than any dramatic outburst.\n\nThe performances are nothing short of exceptional. The lead delivers a nuanced portrayal that balances vulnerability with quiet strength, making the character deeply compelling without ever spelling everything out. There's an authenticity to the performance that draws you in emotionally-you don't just watch this character exist in the space; you feel it.\n\nThe performances in The Housemaid are a major reason the film works as powerfully as it does, with Sydney Sweeney, Amanda Seyfried, Brandon Sklenar, and Michele Morrone each bringing a distinct energy that strengthens the story without ever tipping it into excess. What's impressive is how well these performances complement one another, creating a cast dynamic that feels balanced, believable, and quietly combustible.\n\nSydney Sweeney anchors the film with a performance rooted in emotional honesty. She brings a grounded vulnerability to her role, allowing the audience to connect with her character on a deeply human level. Her strength lies in restraint-small shifts in body language, fleeting expressions, and moments of silence do just as much storytelling as the dialogue. It's a performance that draws empathy without asking for it, making her character's presence feel lived-in rather than performed.\n\nAmanda Seyfried delivers a commanding turn that is both polished and intriguingly layered. She exudes confidence and control, using subtle vocal inflections and precise physicality to suggest depth beneath the surface. Seyfried has an exceptional ability to project warmth and unease simultaneously, which keeps her character fascinating to watch. Every scene she's in carries a sense of tension, driven largely by her ability to imply far more than she ever explicitly reveals.\n\nBrandon Sklenar brings a steady, grounded presence to the film, providing emotional weight without overpowering the narrative. His performance feels natural and understated, offering moments of sincerity that add texture to the story. He plays his role with quiet conviction, making his character feel believable and emotionally accessible, which helps balance the more intense dynamics unfolding around him.\n\nMichele Morrone adds a contrasting intensity, delivering a performance marked by controlled physicality and simmering energy. He communicates as much through posture and presence as he does through dialogue, creating an undercurrent of tension whenever he's on screen. Morrone's performance is confident and compelling, adding another layer to the film's interpersonal dynamics without overshadowing the ensemble.\n\nTogether, the cast forms a cohesive unit, with each actor enhancing the film's psychological depth. Their performances intersect in ways that feel organic and charged, proving that The Housemaid succeeds not just because of its story, but because of the actors who bring its emotional complexity to life.\n\nThe supporting cast is equally impressive, each actor contributing to an ensemble that feels finely tuned and perfectly calibrated. No one overplays their hand, and that subtlety is precisely what makes the tension so effective.\n\nIf you haven't read the book, consider diving in and read Freida McFadden's masterpiece. The book and movie aren't too far apart, but the movie delivers an explosive ending. There are also other books in the Housemaid series.\n\nVisually, The Housemaid is striking without being flashy. The cinematography uses space, light, and framing to reinforce themes of control, observation, and unease. Ordinary domestic settings are transformed into places of quiet intimidation, proving that horror-or at least deep discomfort-doesn't need darkness to thrive. Even the smallest details, from set design to costuming, feel deliberate and symbolic, enriching the story without ever distracting from it.\n\nWhat truly sets this film apart is how it lingers. Rather than relying on shock value, The Housemaid leaves an emotional and psychological imprint. It encourages reflection long after the credits roll, prompting you to reconsider earlier moments and reassess what you thought you understood. That kind of staying power is rare, and it's a testament to the film's smart writing and assured direction.\n\nIn the end, The Housemaid doesn't just clean up-it absolutely sweeps. With its sharp performances, intelligent storytelling, and impeccably maintained tension, this film earns every one of its ten stars. Consider this a glowing recommendation: just remember, once you let The Housemaid into your home, it may rearrange more than you expect. On that note, \"Please, please please\" go and watch The Housemaid at a cinema near you."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4c8a8775-6f4d-44f1-bd82-5bf8e4ef40fa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8ae348cc74fd1128b8ecdd6068b27a300014e2473ee78aada3a0cbdf50a030c9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "movieman6-413-929510", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-24", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is a new thriller directed by Paul Feig, best known for A Simple Favor and Bridesmaids. The film is based on the novel of the same name by Freida McFadden.\n\nMillie Calloway (Sydney Sweeney) tries to leave her past behind and therefore takes a job as a housemaid for Andre Winchester (Brandon Sklenar) and his wife Nina (Amanda Seyfried). During her work, she uncovers hidden secrets and situations within the Winchester couple that change everything.\n\nTogether with screenwriter Rebecca Sonnenshine, Paul Feig effectively brings these secrets and situations to the surface. However, the story occasionally lacks some explanation or detail, which means the film is not always entirely clear, though it remains easy enough to follow.\n\nThese twists are brought out particularly well through the performances of the three lead actors, each of whom reveals their own hidden sides, requiring them to play their roles in very different ways."}}
