{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "157ea8b8-531b-4a66-beb0-d773eb95ee44", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4eccb776fbab96df0642403d0fa6a8245f3f5bb3448ac76be47893e41476726c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "monkey-01982", "rating": null, "date": "2026-01-01", "title": null, "content": "Very weak start and terrible writing for the first half of the movie. Movie improves greatly about halfway in and seemed like it could be an interesting thriller, until it turned into a women-empowerment circlejerk for the last 20min or so. Numerous plot holes exist as well that aren't explained or easily ignored. This movie would have benefited immensely from better directing and scriptwriting."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8d6eea56-70e2-45d2-9688-6d746f3d99cd", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3430044f13c788e0921c04fa58f5e2c891b41dc2a228a2e2eb7b014bdec5bc98"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "gavinp9", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-11", "title": null, "content": "'The Housemaid' is a well-made suburban thriller. We follow Millie (Sweeney), as she gets a new job as a housemaid for an affluent upstate New York family, hired by the Winchesters - wife Nina (Seyfried), husband Andrew (Sklenar) and daughter Cece (Elle). We're then drip-fed new info that changes our perspective one way or another throughout.\n\nIt starts a bit slow, where we mostly have Nina and Millie, and then things slowly start to not add up. Then we get more time with Andrew, and then a big final 30min or so that really pays off. Some pretty good acting and solid score. It's similar-ish to Feig's 'A Simple Favour', but probably better. It's not as funny as 'The Heat' or 'Bridesmaids', but has a few laughs.\n\nSome violence and gore, but not too much, and Sweeney gets her kit off, which is not too shabby. Semi-obvious twist, but the key is the great comeuppance at the end, and good set-up for future films."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c1e74412-475c-4d77-9231-7e0d7d0b2f8a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3154d1107865ff2546885e20fe995d25d1e0ad17d2f1b43a8195c99d305fdcaa"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "imtiaziqbal-75662", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-12", "title": null, "content": "Absoulutely loved this thriller by Ric Roman who immerses the audience into this psycholoogical drama trope but turns out to be far more demented and twisted than you could imagine.\n\nAmanda Seyfried was the the steal of the show as erratic wife with a troubled past while Brandon and Sydney played their parts to perfection.\n\nReminds me of the 90's Thrillers full of surpises ,twists and turns. This movie reveals how people personalities are not what they seem as there's more to story than it's cover."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "14985174-f7e6-4c33-83f9-9fc3cb473596", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "083867d75ef41fae3e1a7e158244f365fbb52b3d0eb1f6c128dbf61ef2544b6c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "fabiolpinheiro1993", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-16", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is not an especially original film-there are plenty of similar thrillers, particularly from the 1990s and early 2000s. However, its story feels more relevant and important than ever, as the issues it tackles are reaching record levels today. Because of that, the film is a very welcome addition, inevitably sparking conversations about its themes and meaning.\n\nTo avoid spoilers, it's difficult to go too deep into the plot, but the development is quite strong and consistently engaging. Despite its heavy subject matter, the film remains entertaining from beginning to end. The plot twists, while effective, could have benefited from a more dramatic treatment. This is actually a rare case where twists feel somewhat underplayed-understandably so-but a bit more impact would have elevated them even further.\n\nAlthough there are allusions to the backgrounds of some characters, I found myself wishing for deeper exploration on that front. The technical aspects of the film are fairly standard for the genre, with nothing particularly noteworthy or standout in terms of cinematography, score, or direction. This feels like a missed opportunity, as all three elements could have significantly elevated the film and helped it truly stand out.\n\nWhat does stand out, however, are the performances from the three leads: Sydney Sweeney, Amanda Seyfried, and Brandon Sklenar. All deliver excellent performances, with Sweeney once again proving herself as a commanding and compelling lead. Still, the true MVP of the film is Amanda Seyfried-unsurprising, given her endless talent and consistency as an actress.\n\nWhile The Housemaid doesn't reinvent the genre, it is twisty, entertaining, relevant, and thought-provoking. It makes for a great cinema experience, and I'm genuinely excited for the sequel to see how it further explores and expands on its premise."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c43bbc9a-319c-48c3-b532-4795b5a41efa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "71a979551a0e8d06b51c0e55ec6a69c270859ce9fe94101956f8569f648a5870"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "measchonewille", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-12-19", "title": null, "content": "The movie was great but you could expect who the villain was but not in a way that made it boring. Sidney Sweeneys acting was mediocre to say but it got better later in the movie, the male leads acting was better but I just couldn't see how he was to be charismatic. Only Amanda was wonderful she played her part perfectly."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "460a7e73-eb2f-49e7-b234-d804c4da3cec", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b9416c0899fabef7755be30ea305a4b4e39c52fab6d31953917b45c369c0b8d1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "vampiresrule347", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-21", "title": null, "content": "Please don't expect it to be an exact replica of the book, as I did, because when you're watching something, it's a different medium, so certain elements have to be altered. However, they did adapt important aspects of the book. The only aspect that felt rushed was the chemistry between the characters. I also didn't appreciate how Enzo's character was minimized, except for that. The two lead female characters were fantastic, and so was the male lead."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f1aa8b47-5f78-4cc3-b3cc-8453509b187c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.252167", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ae711770fab1805b25a64c2e506302ec788500a7ef21ae03cf83a47328ee0136"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "rgkarim", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-21", "title": null, "content": "LIKES: Solid Setting Great Production Value Decent Pacing Great Information Rather Limited Loose Ends Sensual Drama Good Character Development Thrilling Elements Good Dark Comedy Use Accurate Per My Friend The Acting Is The Heart DISLIKES: A Tad Predictable Some Intense Moments A Tad Contrived It Is Long One Character Needed some More Time\n\nSummary: I went in this movie with expectations that it would be another Drama book massacred into a new Grey's Anatomy-like session with attractive stars and little sustenance outside of superficial qualities of sex and scandal. Fortunately, they were wrong. The Housemaid starts with a great setting, a realistic suburban neighborhood with gorgeous views, eclectic tastes, and plenty of areas to give some intense moments. Fantastic production qualities bring this house to life, mixing great cinematography, sound editing, and direction to bring the book to life and give you as many facets of this odd situation as possible. I found myself able to follow all of the information that was held in this book, with surprisingly detailed pieces that didn't feel bloated, overloaded, or unnecessary for the most part. Feig's direction has brought something to life, a very powerful translation from the book to the movie, as the transcription seems to get most of the details accurate (according to my friend), and takes liberties to give a little more edge, thrills, and movie flair to make it more engaging. Loose ends feel very minimal, even the ending, making sure to give everyone what they need to conclude this tale, while also setting up for a sequel, should they pursue the other books. It maintains good character development, granting levels of detail one would find in a book (to some extent), but again not bloating the time with anything that felt a waste or used for a time filler. Sensual elements arise in the right places, giving you plenty of thrills, drama, and the physically appealing elements that several members in my theater made sound effects for their enjoyment. Dark comedy finds its place at the right times, lines that feel well-timed and delivered with a venomous bite that leaves behind damaging effects far after the acidic words drip out. And all of this comes together in a balanced manner to be this invigorating and intriguing film, I had not expected to be so enjoyable to watch. Yet, it's the acting, I think, that brings much of this to life, with performances that bring our actors to incredible levels of haunting edginess that make a thriller like this so enjoyable to watch. Sweeney's got her usual tricks, the spectrum not as ranged as her co-actress, but so masterful that I can't help but be drawn into her performance. Seyfried surprised me with her range of emotions and the sheer terror of how believable she can shift between so many complex mindsets, with such startling accuracy, and still craft such an alluring character. Brandon Sklenar was sensational in his role, delivering lines with a rapier-sharp and precise stabs that do everything you need for such a bridging role between so many characters. Their chemistry is incredible, and to bring such fierceness to the role was not something I was expecting to be such a strong element to the movie.\n\nMy Dislikes are fewer in this film, but as a warning, I'm not the biggest fan of her work and don't have the bias that superfans might think. The movie has plenty of lines added or focused to convey the direction the film is going, sometimes doing too good a job of preparing you for what is about to come. Such twists are maximized with surprise, and I don't quite think they got that with these major hints. In addition, the movie is a bit contrived, requiring some suspension of logic and lapses in judgment to ignore the trouble that is brewing. I guess that's part of the fun, but these elements do little, nor do some of the more intense moments do for my friends. While it's not the most disturbing, those with constitutions not set to some triggering material need to brace themselves for the chaos to come. And as many have said, the film is a tad longer than I suspected, running over two hours. While the pacing is good, that investment means limited showtimes could feel longer than you want. Finally, some information pieces could have used some time, especially in regards to one character or two who could have gotten a little more time and involvement, something the book does better.\n\nThe VERDICT: In the end, The Housemaid was much better than I expected. A solid book-to-movie conversion on many elements, the film seems to do the book justice and adds a bit more dramatic energy to the book to serve some more fulfilling justice without compromising most of the integrity. The production quality is high, the humor is integrated strongly, and I think that the balance of information, thrills, and drama is one of the better elements I've seen in a long time. With an incredible cast to bring the material to life, The Housemaid only continues to be a movie I can recommend, worthy of the theater for those ready for a twisty, turny, and deeper film than I had expected. Sure, it's not a perfect conversion, as some changes may not suit some of the fans, and the length of the film may be difficult, given the fleeting attention spans many have told me they suffer from. In addition, this film still has a bit of a contrived plot and some darker elements that may be disturbing to watch without a friend or some means to cope with the intense displays. Still, when I factor everything together, I give The Housemaid: Drama/Thriller: 8.0-8.5 Movie Overall: 7.5-8.0."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8bd79314-af43-4008-bf0a-3b13d4663a5a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.254173", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c23a91fbb86fa516db7989b346ee146c9799bc5436db9b4fb66b5d53a68b89c9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "burlesonjesse5", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-26", "title": null, "content": "The Housemaid is about um, housemaids and garrets and sudden tics and well, non-straight-faced discipline. It's a conceptual thriller mind you, layered and upsetting and possibly 20 minutes too long, with a lily white look and lots of sanguinary imagery. \"Housemaid\", well it has to do with a live-in menial who gets hired by a rich couple that has well, some evil baggage amidst their big-arse abode, their snobby friends, and their swank rides. \"So why do you want this job?\" Uh, my thoughts exactly.\n\n\"Housemaid\", yeah it's directed by Mount Clemens, Michigan native Paul Feig, a guy who never met a film genre or a cinematic grain he couldn't transition to and fro. Here he turns the psychological screws, giving The Housemaid enough twists and turns and flexed paradox to power freaking Shanghai on the low. I mean you think you know where the flick is headed until you don't, as the Feig man adds about five extra codas, a fem-happy soundtrack, and plenty of curdling ichor. \"I need this job.\" You said it star Sydney Sweeney, not me.\n\nPerfect casting in the form of Amanda Seyfried, Sweeny, and Brandon Sklenar. A piece of dialogue that might rank up there with On the Waterfront's \"I coulda been a contender! (\"I need a sandwich!).\" Sterile-looking New Jersey locales where the five story dwelling is the star. Paul Feig stirring the Flowers in the Attic lump while harboring on the possible, Lifetime Television tip. Yup, that's what makes The Housemaid fairly recommendable. I 