{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "be1f4646-aae4-4710-89de-12f5cad0a077", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.254173", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "62ac597101888bd7dc5bdb3e6e4bca9dccb35307f36b43555a208008ed111b93"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "konradvul", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "For the first half of the movie, I honestly thought its main \"highlight\" was simply that Sydney Sweeney gets naked. Thankfully, the second half becomes slightly less absurd once the film attempts to explain what was happening earlier. However, by then, the damage is already done.\n\nThe story is so unrealistic, poorly thought through, and weakly executed that it's hard to take the film seriously. I wouldn't even classify it as a thriller; its absurdity often provokes an unintended smile rather than tension or suspense.\n\nAmanda Seyfried delivers a solid performance and does not disappoint, but the same cannot be said for Sydney Sweeney. She may have other talents, but convincing acting is unfortunately not one of them here.\n\nThe story is riddled with plot holes, and any hope for a well-developed or intelligent conclusion quickly collapses into pure ridiculousness. Overall, the film struggles to find coherence, credibility, or emotional impact, and ends up feeling more unintentionally comedic than thrilling."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8ea968dc-0fce-44ca-bd0e-46b0ba243a3c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:23.254173", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "bd4ad936f13a1435be0a9d84c2da0c87dca7c3ab9b27230fa96141fe0d0ded2f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt27543632", "author": "MichaelK-9652", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-12-22", "title": null, "content": "The plot wanders around aimlessly like it lost its keys halfway through the first act and never bothered to look for them. Characters appear, deliver lines that sound like rejected fortune-cookie quotes, and then disappear with no explanation. By the end, I wasn't sure who I was supposed to care about-or why I was still awake.\n\nThe acting is... present. Faces move, voices happen, emotions are implied rather than felt. One performance in particular feels like the actor was reading the script for the first time while the camera was already rolling. If confusion were an acting choice, this cast committed hard.\n\nVisually, the movie tries very hard to look \"important,\" which usually means dim lighting and long, slow shots of nothing. There are several moments where the camera just stares at something, daring you to find meaning in it. I did not accept the challenge."}}
